Facebook oversight, Apple v Epic, marketplace woes, Twitter paywalls, hacking a pipeline, and Warren Buffet's millennium bug






















Benedict's Newsletter
FREE EDITION / Tuesday 11 May, 2021
What mattered in tech this week?




























MY WORK / NEWS / IDEAS / OUTSIDE / DATA


























Resetting the app store
We‚Äôve been arguing about app stores for a decade, but now the EU is going to change the rules. Will that actually matter, or is it just a $10bn wealth transfer to a few games companies?¬†Link
Does Amazon know what it sells?
Amazon has scaled indefinitely by treating every product as an interchangeable packet, and by not caring what they are, only what they weigh. At a fundamental level, it doesn‚Äôt know what it sells. What would happen if it could change that?¬†Link


























MY WORK / NEWS / IDEAS / OUTSIDE / DATA


























Trump versus Facebook
Facebook's independent oversight board had been asked to rule on FB's suspension of Trump earlier this year, and this week it kicked the question back to FB, saying that FB needs to present more systematic and coherent criteria (the 'Mark Says So' problem).
Facebook, and to a lesser extent Twitter and Youtube, have reach and control over public speech that is quite different to newspapers or TV, yet when they make¬†decisions around this they have¬†neither the implicit legitimacy that comes from a social consensus around how newspapers or TV work, nor the explicit legitimacy of a state. And a 35-year-old product manager in Menlo Park doesn't want to decide the basis for political speech. Hence, 'let's have an external board of experts' - but if it's still Facebook's eternal board, what does external mean? Who decides? How does that intersect with the US constitution's bar on state control of speech? With the 90% of FB users outside the USA? With 'Section 230'? Everyone had their answer written before the result.¬†Link
Apple versus Epic in court
The Apple/Epic App Store court case started this week. It mostly turns on legal arguments and court precedents around how to define the market, the platform and the payment system, not the facts or any 'smoking gun' emails, and a lot of US antitrust lawyers seem to think Epic's case is pretty weak (ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è). As I've written before, the EU has already effectively decided in favour of Spotify, so regardless of this case there are big changes coming. But either way, cases like this generally produce a lot of interesting disclosure:
Epic produced lots of internal Apple emails showing how many scams and problems there are in store management, aiming to undermine Apple's 'we curate the store' argument. But these are mostly from 5-10 years ago (when it was having huge problems scaling) and could equally well show how necessary curation is
Apple produced Epic emails showing it planned the whole fight a year in advance and is investing massively in its own store
From outside, the most interesting thing is the app store operating data: how Apple scans for malware and API abuse (no, the security is not all in the sandbox), how many apps are submitted and which ones are rejected. Also, there are only 17k Watch apps: like Amazon's Alexa, the Apple Watch is a huge success but has largely failed as an app platform.
Links:¬†The court page,¬†Apple metrics PDF
Who owns a Marketplace customer? Questions for Amazon
60% of Amazon ecommerce volume is buying from third parties through Marketplace - you're buying on Amazon but not from Amazon. So whose business is that? Who owns the customer in a platform business, and who is making the sale? (Epic might make the same point.) Three stories this week:
Apparently, some Amazon ecommerce people had access to data on third party Marketplace sales, which Amazon has always said should not happen. Amazon is both retailer and platform, and while it's normal for a retailer to compete with its suppliers (all retailers always have!) giving data on its Marketplace customers to its retail team is a conflict of interest.
A court in a lawsuit over a defective hoverboard (remember those?) found that Amazon is liable for damage caused by defective Marketplace products. So who is really making the sale?
Someone found a database of companies and buyers participating in a large-scale project to sell fake Amazon reviews, and Amazon seems to have reacted by banning (temporarily?) some of the largest Chinese marketplace vendors (Aukey, Tomtop etc) - suddenly their pages are empty.
Links:¬†data access,¬†liability lawsuit,¬†China paid reviews,¬†Aukey
Youtube versus Roku
Connected, 'smart' TV has quietly taken a significant gatekeeping role in the TV business, with platform providers both getting into so-called 'addressable advertising' (see the IAB paper below) and starting to charge for placement (ITV in the UK recently complained that Amazon wanted them to bid against Netflix). Now Roku and Youtube are fighting, accusing each other of lying about the nature of the dispute, and trying to block each other. (Also, note how absent Apple is from these conversions - such strategic failure.)¬†Link
YahAol changes hands
As rumoured last week, a PE firm (Apollo) bought the vestiges of Yahoo and AOL from Verizon. These kinds of business have a very long half-life but zero chance of turning around - at some point in the future there'll be nothing left but a lawyer's office licensing out the brand name, like Polaroid or Pan-Am.¬†Link,¬†Microsoft's $45bn bid
Google goes back to work, 30/20
As vaccines roll out, we're all wondering what a return to work really looks like. Google says three days in the office and two days out (for most people), and suggest that means it will need the same (or perhaps even more) square footage. If you're a restaurant next to the Google building in Manhattan, that might mean 40% less footfall.¬†Link
The next Apple Watch adds glucose and blood alcohol?
From the rumour mill: people have been trying to do needle-free glucose monitoring for ages, but Apple (and its suppliers) might have cracked it. More generally - Apple launched the watch with lots of ideas for what it might be (fashion? luxury? app platform?) but fitness and health is the one that's worked.¬†Link
Amazon's local network
With Apple's 'Find My' local wireless network now open to third parties, it's also worth looking at Amazon's equivalent, based on Alexa and Ring devices, which now has a partnership with Tile. Local mesh was always a fantasy as a competitor to cellular (very basic laws of physics barriers) but it's finally becoming interesting for very low power, low cost, low bandwidth applications - 'find my bag' is the first use case but there might be other, bigger ones.¬†Link
Twitter expands to paywalls
Twitter's new 'hey, maybe we should execute!' strategy continues with the acquisition of Scroll, which makes a federated pay wall (pay one monthly subscription and your money is distributed to participating sites based on your readership). It can integrate this into the mobile in-app browser for a frictionless signup, and link to Twitter payment. It also launched a beta of tip jars and opened its clubhouse clone 'Spaces' to anyone with more than 600 followers.
But more generally - the growth of viable tools and consumer behaviours around paying for content, even if you're not a giant like the NY Times, and in parallel with the death of ad cookies, is one of the more interesting trends on the consumer internet right now.¬†Link
Chip shortage is really hurting car companies
The global chip supply chain crunch has affected Apple and Samsung but the real impact remains in the car industry, where the lack of a few $10 chips for each car has halted entire production lines. Now car companies are stripping out features just to get production moving again.¬†Link
Apple's targeted, tracked ad system
With iOS 14.5, Apple switched all 3rd party cross-app tracking to opt-in (ATT), and did the same to app install ads (IDFA), while leaving its own 1st party tracking switched on by default. Now it's adding its own app install ads to App Store search, and of course has its own team working on 'ad relevance' (AKA, well, tracking and targeting). Apple's PR around 'privacy' and 'tracking' has been as brilliant as its PR around in-app payment has been terrible. Links:¬†Search ads,¬†'Ad relevance' jobs
Tesla legal: "Ignore what Elon says about autonomy"
Elon Musk has been claiming that Tesla will have 'Level 5' full autonomy working any day now for years, while never shipping anything close, and people working in autonomy have always rolled their eyes. Real L5 is 5-10 years away and has been for, well, 5-10 years. But now we see that Tesla itself acknowledged to the Californian government that Tesla actually only has Level 2 'assisted cruise control' working. ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è¬†Link
Today in cyber
Two big breaches this week: both a US hospital system and a gasoline pipeline that supplies 45% of the US east coast's needs were shut down by ransomware. This is all a very big deal, in slow motion.¬†Hospital system,¬†Pipeline
UK spies block Chinese tech for 'smart cities'
Equally, the UK intelligence services have blocked a number of local councils from buying and deploying 'smart city' systems from Chinese vendors. This is partly about straightforward espionage (though really, what can the MSS do with traffic cameras and parking tickets in Bournemouth?) but much more about control and the scope for disruption: do you want potentially critical infrastructure to depend on the goodwill of the Chinese state, given in recent years it's demonstrated quite what that 'goodwill' might look like?¬†Link


























MY WORK / NEWS / IDEAS / OUTSIDE / DATA


























Ideas from around the web
Passionate opinion piece in the New York Times, from a member of the editorial board, calling for the government to ban 'dark patterns' such as, say, making it hard to unsubscribe. To unsubscribe from the New York Times, you have to telephone them, in business hours, and let them try to talk you out of it.¬†Link
NY Times profile of Nick Clegg's role in Facebook decisions around Trump and political advertising.¬†Link¬†($)
Google edges towards the end of passwords.¬†Link
The ad industry is trying to work out what effects Apple's ATT will have.¬†Link
A large Oxford study on screen time, social media and depression found, well, no real link at all.¬†Link
'Philip DeFranco' and YouTube news-influencers. Prepare to feel old.¬†Link
Andrew Ng on AI hype and why so many cool papers are hard to generalise.¬†Link
Cloud kitchens keep getting more interesting.¬†Gay Burger¬†merged the model with influencing and¬†Five Guys burgers¬†has opened its first outlet.
Someone mailed an AirTag to themselves to see if they could track its route.¬†Link
Twitch's intersection with music.¬†Link
Protocol interview with the head of FB Messenger, Stan Chudnovsky.¬†Link
Interesting piece pointing out that the new Canon DSLR can capture still-quality images at 30 frames per second - in effect, you can now record video at photo quality and pick any frame you want.¬†Link
An argument that Amazon will do best from the death of cookies and the push to 1st party data.¬†Link
IAB report on the growth of programatic TV advertising, also known as 'addressable TV'. See also Amazon, and the Roku fight.¬†Link¬†(PDF)


























